{"id":"2006.01937","submitter":"Alexander Razborov","authors":"Alexander Razborov","title":"An Extremal Problem Motivated by Triangle-Free Strongly Regular Graphs","comments":"34 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We introduce the following combinatorial problem. Let $G$ be a triangle-free\nregular graph with edge density $\\rho$. What is the minimum value $a(\\rho)$ for\nwhich there always exist two non-adjacent vertices such that the density of\ntheir common neighborhood is $\\leq a(\\rho)$? We prove a variety of upper bounds\non the function $a(\\rho)$ that are tight for the values $\\rho=2/5,\\ 5/16,\\\n3/10,\\ 11/50$, with $C_5$, Clebsch, Petersen and Higman-Sims being respective\nextremal configurations. Our proofs are entirely combinatorial and are largely\nbased on counting densities in the style of flag algebras. For small values of\n$\\rho$, our bound attaches a combinatorial meaning to Krein conditions that\nmight be interesting in its own right. We also prove that for any $\\epsilon>0$\nthere are only finitely many values of $\\rho$ with $a(\\rho)\\geq\\epsilon$ but\nthis finiteness result is somewhat purely existential (the bound is double\nexponential in $1/\\epsilon$).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 2 Jun 2020 20:40:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-06-04"}
