{"id":"2006.02159","submitter":"Iv\\'an Le\\'on","authors":"Iv\\'an Le\\'on and Diego Paz\\'o","title":"Quasi phase reduction of all-to-all strongly coupled $\\lambda-\\omega$\n  oscillators near incoherent states","comments":"11 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 102, 042203 (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.102.042203","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.AO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The dynamics of an ensemble of $N$ weakly coupled limit-cycle oscillators can\nbe captured by their $N$ phases using standard phase reduction techniques.\nHowever, it is a phenomenological fact that all-to-all strongly coupled\nlimit-cycle oscillators may behave as \"quasiphase oscillators\", evidencing the\nneed of novel reduction strategies. We introduce here quasi phase reduction\n(QPR), a scheme suited for identical oscillators with polar symmetry\n($\\lambda-\\omega$ systems). By applying QPR we achieve a reduction to $N+2$\ndegrees of freedom: $N$ phase oscillators interacting through one independent\ncomplex variable. This \"quasi phase model\" is asymptotically valid in the\nneighborhood of incoherent states, irrespective of the coupling strength. The\neffectiveness of QPR is illustrated in a particular case, an ensemble of\nStuart-Landau oscillators, obtaining exact stability boundaries of uniform and\nnonuniform incoherent states for a variety of couplings. An extension of QPR\nbeyond the neighborhood of incoherence is also explored. Finally, a general QPR\nmodel with $N+2M$ degrees of freedom is obtained for coupling through the first\n$M$ harmonics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 3 Jun 2020 10:54:23 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 11 Aug 2020 10:16:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-10-14"}
